# Urfael remote bridges (Telegram / Discord / Slack / iMessage / Email / Matrix / Signal / WhatsApp). Copy to ~/.claude/urfael/bridge.env and `chmod 600`. NEVER commit.
#
# Remote access is OPT-IN and SANDBOXED: every remote message is forced into the restricted 'untrusted'
# profile (no bypassPermissions even with URFAEL_YOLO, no computer-use, read/search/web/notes only), and
# ONLY the single owner id below is ever answered — every other sender is dropped before the brain sees it.
# Leave a section blank to disable that channel. With this file absent, bridges and phone notifications
# are simply off.

# --- Telegram (works on Node 18+) ---
# 1. Create a bot: message @BotFather -> /newbot -> copy the token.
# 2. Get your numeric chat id: message @userinfobot, or open https://api.telegram.org/bot<token>/getUpdates
#    after you DM your bot, and read message.chat.id.
TELEGRAM_BOT_TOKEN=
TELEGRAM_OWNER_CHAT_ID=

# --- Discord (needs Node 22+ for the built-in WebSocket) ---
# 1. Create an application + bot at https://discord.com/developers/applications
# 2. Under the bot, ENABLE the "MESSAGE CONTENT INTENT" (privileged) so it can read your DMs.
# 3. Invite the bot, then DM it. Get your numeric user id: Settings -> Advanced -> Developer Mode,
#    then right-click your name -> Copy User ID.
DISCORD_BOT_TOKEN=
DISCORD_OWNER_USER_ID=

# --- Slack (Socket Mode — needs Node 22+ for the built-in WebSocket) ---
# 1. Create an app at https://api.slack.com/apps (from scratch).
# 2. Enable Socket Mode (Settings -> Socket Mode). That generates an app-level token (xapp-…) with the
#    connections:write scope -> that is SLACK_APP_TOKEN.
# 3. Under "OAuth & Permissions", add Bot Token Scopes: chat:write, im:history, im:read. Install the app to
#    your workspace and copy the Bot User OAuth Token (xoxb-…) -> SLACK_BOT_TOKEN.
# 4. Under "Event Subscriptions" (Socket Mode), subscribe to the bot event: message.im. Reinstall if prompted.
# 5. Get your own user id: click your profile -> "Copy member ID" (U…), or any user-id helper -> SLACK_OWNER_USER_ID.
#    Then DM the app. Only that one user id is ever answered; everyone else is dropped before the brain.
SLACK_APP_TOKEN=
SLACK_BOT_TOKEN=
SLACK_OWNER_USER_ID=

# --- iMessage (macOS ONLY, best-effort — REQUIRES Full Disk Access) ---
# Reads ~/Library/Messages/chat.db read-only and replies via the Messages app over AppleScript. The process
# that runs the bridge MUST have Full Disk Access (System Settings -> Privacy & Security -> Full Disk Access);
# add your terminal/launchd runner there or the bridge exits with a clear message. Needs the sqlite3 CLI.
# IMESSAGE_OWNER_HANDLE is the EXACT handle as it appears in Messages: a phone in +E.164 form (e.g. +15551234567)
# or the Apple ID email. Only inbound messages from this one handle are ever read or answered.
# IMESSAGE_POLL_SECS is how often to check for new messages (default 4).
IMESSAGE_OWNER_HANDLE=
IMESSAGE_POLL_SECS=4

# --- Email (IMAP over TLS — works on Node 18+, no extra deps) ---
# Inbound IMAP IDLE, DRAFT-ONLY out: this bridge NEVER sends mail. Each allowlisted, unread message is relayed
# to the sandboxed brain and the reply is saved as a DRAFT (a 'Re: …' to the original sender) in your Drafts
# mailbox for you to review and send yourself. It opens NO inbound port and connects ONLY to your IMAP server.
# 1. EMAIL_IMAP_HOST / EMAIL_IMAP_PORT: your provider's IMAP host (e.g. imap.gmail.com) and TLS port (993).
# 2. EMAIL_USER: the full mailbox address you log in with.
# 3. EMAIL_PASS: an APP-SPECIFIC password (NOT your real account password). Gmail: turn on 2FA, then create an
#    App Password (myaccount.google.com > Security > App passwords). Other providers have an equivalent.
# 4. EMAIL_ALLOWED_SENDERS: comma-separated From addresses. ONLY mail whose From is one of these is ever relayed
#    — every other sender is dropped before the brain sees it. Leave blank and the bridge refuses to start.
# 5. EMAIL_DRAFT_MAILBOX: where drafts are appended (default 'Drafts'; Gmail may need '[Gmail]/Drafts').
# 6. EMAIL_POLL_SECS: IDLE fallback / re-check interval in seconds (default 60, floor 10).
EMAIL_IMAP_HOST=
EMAIL_IMAP_PORT=993
EMAIL_USER=
EMAIL_PASS=
EMAIL_ALLOWED_SENDERS=
EMAIL_DRAFT_MAILBOX=Drafts
EMAIL_POLL_SECS=60

# --- Idle-suspend for the OUTBOUND pollers (opt-in, default OFF) ---
# These are PROCESS environment variables (set them in your launchd/systemd unit or shell for BOTH the daemon and
# the bridge processes), NOT bridge.env keys. Listed here only for discoverability.
# URFAEL_IDLE_SUSPEND=1 makes a self-timed outbound poller stretch its OWN poll cadence once you have gone quiet,
# then snap back to the hot cadence on your next message or on a scheduled/heartbeat push. It changes ONLY how long
# the loop sleeps: the brain daemon, its 0600 socket, and the allowlist gate are untouched (no new inbound port),
# and a woken poll re-runs the same allowlist gate before any message reaches the brain. Default OFF => the poller
# behavior is byte-identical. Fail-safe: the worst case is a bounded first-catch latency (<= the probe cadence),
# never a lost message. SCOPE: it targets iMessage (the only true 4s busy-poller) and email's non-IDLE fallback
# (secondary, and a no-op at the default knobs since email's fallback is already 60s). The long-poll bridges
# (Telegram/Matrix), the IMAP IDLE push path, the Signal streaming subprocess, and the WebSocket-heartbeat bridges
# (Discord/Slack/QQ/SimpleX) are intentionally NOT suspended, because they are already idle-cheap server-side.
# Tuning knobs (inert unless URFAEL_IDLE_SUSPEND is on):
#   URFAEL_IDLE_AFTER_MIN  minutes of no owner activity before a poller drops to the probe cadence (default 5)
#   URFAEL_IDLE_PROBE_SECS the low-frequency idle probe cadence, in seconds (default 60; floored so it is never
#                          faster than the bridge's native poll interval, so the first-catch latency ceiling)
# URFAEL_IDLE_SUSPEND=1
# URFAEL_IDLE_AFTER_MIN=5
# URFAEL_IDLE_PROBE_SECS=60

# --- Matrix (pure HTTPS client-server API — works on Node 18+, no extra deps, NO inbound port) ---
# Outbound long-poll only: we GET /_matrix/client/v3/sync and relay your messages to the sandboxed brain, then
# reply with PUT .../send/m.room.message. ONLY messages from MATRIX_OWNER_USER_ID are ever answered.
# 1. MATRIX_HOMESERVER: your homeserver's https base url, e.g. https://matrix.org (no trailing slash).
# 2. MATRIX_TOKEN: an access token for a bot/second account. Easiest: in Element, log in as that account, then
#    Settings -> Help & About -> Advanced -> "Access Token". Or POST /_matrix/client/v3/login with a password.
#    Treat it like a password — it grants full control of that account. Never commit it.
# 3. MATRIX_OWNER_USER_ID: YOUR matrix id in @user:server form (e.g. @maxim:matrix.org). Only this sender is
#    answered; everyone else is dropped before the brain. Make sure the bot account shares a room with you.
# 4. MATRIX_ROOM_ID (optional): a room id (!abc123:server) to restrict to a single room AND the destination for
#    --notify pushes. Leave blank to listen in every room the bot account has joined (still owner-only).
MATRIX_HOMESERVER=
MATRIX_TOKEN=
MATRIX_OWNER_USER_ID=
MATRIX_ROOM_ID=

# --- Signal (wraps the user-installed signal-cli binary — NO inbound port, no npm dep) ---
# REQUIRES signal-cli (https://github.com/AsamK/signal-cli) installed and the SIGNAL_ACCOUNT number registered
# or linked as a device. We spawn `signal-cli -a ACCOUNT receive --json`, relay dataMessages from the one
# allowlisted sender to the sandboxed brain, and reply via `signal-cli -a ACCOUNT send`. The bridge exits with a
# clear message if signal-cli is missing.
# 1. SIGNAL_CLI_PATH: path to the binary (default 'signal-cli'; set an absolute path if it's not on PATH).
# 2. SIGNAL_ACCOUNT: the +E.164 number the bridge sends/receives as (e.g. +15551230000) — must be linked already.
#    Link it once: `signal-cli link -n urfael` (scan the QR from your phone) or register a dedicated number.
# 3. SIGNAL_OWNER_NUMBER: the +E.164 number of the single allowlisted sender (your phone). Only messages from
#    this number are ever read or answered; everyone else is dropped before the brain.
# 4. SIGNAL_OWNER_UUID (optional): newer signal-cli builds may report only a sourceUuid (no number) on incoming
#    messages. If your owner messages get dropped, set this to your account UUID (from `signal-cli listIdentities`)
#    — the bridge then accepts a match on the number OR the UUID (still fail-closed to just you).
SIGNAL_CLI_PATH=signal-cli
SIGNAL_ACCOUNT=
SIGNAL_OWNER_NUMBER=
SIGNAL_OWNER_UUID=

# --- WhatsApp (Meta Cloud API) — *** THE ONE BRIDGE WITH AN INBOUND WEBHOOK *** ---
# Every other Urfael bridge is outbound-only. WhatsApp's Cloud API only delivers messages by POSTing a webhook,
# so this bridge MUST listen. We contain it tightly:
#   - the server BINDS TO 127.0.0.1 ONLY — it is never on the network directly. You run a tunnel
#     (e.g. `cloudflared tunnel --url http://127.0.0.1:8788`, or ngrok, or a reverse proxy) and give Meta the
#     tunnel's HTTPS url + your verify token. The tunnel is the only public surface; the bridge itself is loopback.
#   - every POST's X-Hub-Signature-256 HMAC is verified with WHATSAPP_APP_SECRET (constant-time) BEFORE the body
#     is parsed, and any message whose `from` != WHATSAPP_OWNER_NUMBER is dropped before the brain.
# TRADEOFF: accepting inbound webhooks is a larger attack surface than the long-poll bridges. If you don't need
# WhatsApp, leave this section blank and the bridge stays off. Prefer a tunnel that adds its own auth if possible.
# 1. WHATSAPP_TOKEN: a Graph API access token for your WhatsApp Business app (System User token recommended;
#    temporary tokens expire). developers.facebook.com -> your app -> WhatsApp -> API Setup.
# 2. WHATSAPP_PHONE_ID: the Phone number ID shown on that same API Setup page (NOT the phone number itself).
# 3. WHATSAPP_OWNER_NUMBER: your WhatsApp number in international digits (e.g. 15551230000; +/spaces are ignored).
#    Only messages from this number are answered; everyone else is dropped before the brain.
# 4. WHATSAPP_APP_SECRET: your Meta app's App Secret (Settings -> Basic). Used to verify the webhook HMAC.
# 5. WHATSAPP_VERIFY_TOKEN: any random string you choose; paste the SAME value into Meta's webhook config so the
#    one-time GET verification handshake succeeds.
# 6. WHATSAPP_WEBHOOK_PORT: local loopback port to listen on (default 8788); point your tunnel at this port.
WHATSAPP_TOKEN=
WHATSAPP_PHONE_ID=
WHATSAPP_OWNER_NUMBER=
WHATSAPP_APP_SECRET=
WHATSAPP_VERIFY_TOKEN=
WHATSAPP_WEBHOOK_PORT=8788
